1
00:02:10,500 --> 00:02:12,961
Help!

2
00:02:23,640 --> 00:02:26,894
It's not what you think.

3
00:02:34,568 --> 00:02:38,365
Well, it's partly what you think, but, er...

4
00:02:38,531 --> 00:02:41,368
Oh, it's so complicated.

5
00:03:43,147 --> 00:03:47,985
Oh, God, help me! Please!
You can't be the man I'm about to marry.

6
00:03:48,152 --> 00:03:52,282
Don't tell me that my fiancé is...
that my fiancé is a...

7
00:03:54,451 --> 00:03:59,499
Haunted Honeymoon, starring Larry Abbot,
will continue after this news update.

8
00:03:59,666 --> 00:04:06,589
Stay tuned for the chilling conclusion of this
week's tale from Manhattan Mystery Theatre.

9
00:04:06,756 --> 00:04:11,136
- Don't touch that dial. We'll be right back.
- You're off the air.

10
00:04:11,303 --> 00:04:14,391
OK, boys. You've got two minutes. Go.

11
00:04:14,556 --> 00:04:20,814
Listen, pal, I'm not a boy and I don't want
to be referred to as one of the boys.

12
00:04:25,736 --> 00:04:30,033
Hey, hey, hey! Guys, guys! Gal...
One at a time, huh?

13
00:04:30,199 --> 00:04:33,412
- Are you two getting married Sunday?
- Only if it rains.

14
00:04:33,413 --> 00:04:35,603
I got tickets for the World Series.

15
00:04:35,664 --> 00:04:39,336
- When did he ask you?
- After strangling me in Curse of the Mummy.

16
00:04:39,503 --> 00:04:41,797
- Say yes right away?
- Bet your sweet patoot.

17
00:04:41,964 --> 00:04:44,966
- How do you spell "patoot"?
- Any way you like.

18
00:04:45,132 --> 00:04:50,015
You've been in lots of shows that went bust.
How's it feel to own a hit?

19
00:04:50,181 --> 00:04:52,768
I don't own her, I'm just marrying her.

20
00:04:52,933 --> 00:04:55,020
No, I mean the radio show.

21
00:04:55,186 --> 00:05:00,775
Sure, I'm on top of the world 'cause I got
the number one show. That's just luck.

22
00:05:00,944 --> 00:05:04,280
I'm head-over-heels in love
with the best girl in the world.

23
00:05:04,448 --> 00:05:06,867
That's not luck, that's God smiling on me.

24
00:05:07,032 --> 00:05:09,954
When Vickie said yes to me...

25
00:05:14,418 --> 00:05:17,420
From the minute Vickie said yes...

26
00:05:25,012 --> 00:05:29,642
He bought a double mattress and a new stove.

27
00:05:29,810 --> 00:05:35,565
- How's her cooking? Have you tasted it yet?
- Sure, but we're getting married anyway.

28
00:05:35,734 --> 00:05:38,986
- Vickie, how'd he ask you?
- Give us a break.

29
00:05:39,152 --> 00:05:43,533
Your fans love this stuff.
Come on, Vickie. Was he romantic?

30
00:05:43,700 --> 00:05:46,453
It was like in the movies. Honest to God.

31
00:05:46,621 --> 00:05:48,872
We're walking along in the moonlight.

32
00:05:49,040 --> 00:05:52,334
He gets down on one knee,
looks at me and says...

33
00:05:54,045 --> 00:05:56,298
It's almost airtime, gentlemen.

34
00:05:56,465 --> 00:05:59,343
OK, boys, that's it.

35
00:05:59,509 --> 00:06:02,888
We're giving you a page of coverage here.

36
00:06:03,055 --> 00:06:05,183
Give 'em a break, will ya?

37
00:06:07,852 --> 00:06:10,314
Can we have a level first violin, please?

38
00:06:10,480 --> 00:06:14,777
- Well, Larry's certainly in good form today.
- The show isn't over.

39
00:06:14,943 --> 00:06:19,491
- You can see he's fine today, Charlie.
- The show isn't over yet.

40
00:06:21,909 --> 00:06:24,747
Eddy, are you there? I don't see you.

41
00:06:26,457 --> 00:06:29,961
Could we hear a little bit of the storm, please?

42
00:06:56,532 --> 00:06:58,618
That's fine, Eddy.

43
00:06:58,785 --> 00:07:02,039
Ten seconds, everyone.

44
00:07:02,204 --> 00:07:03,792
- Say, Eddy...
- Huh?

45
00:07:03,957 --> 00:07:06,586
- Is my tie straight?
- What?

46
00:07:06,751 --> 00:07:11,633
- My tie, is it straight?
- Your tie's fine.

47
00:07:11,800 --> 00:07:16,555
- No, but is it straight?
- Yeah, your tie is straight.

48
00:07:16,721 --> 00:07:21,228
- Say "I swear to God your tie is straight".
- I swear to God.

49
00:07:21,394 --> 00:07:22,980
- Thanks, Eddy.
- Sh!

50
00:07:26,315 --> 00:07:30,113
Ralston Purina Checkerboard Square,
makers of Purina Dog Chow, presents

51
00:07:30,279 --> 00:07:33,574
Manhattan Mystery Theatre.

52
00:07:33,741 --> 00:07:36,370
Hello again. Still there?

53
00:07:36,535 --> 00:07:39,247
This is your host speaking.

54
00:07:39,414 --> 00:07:44,295
And now, friends, brace yourselves
for the chilling conclusion...

55
00:07:44,462 --> 00:07:47,882
to tonight's tale of horror, entitled...

56
00:07:49,509 --> 00:07:53,097
Haunted Honeymoon.

57
00:07:57,350 --> 00:08:00,063
Lady Wolfington is speaking on the telephone...

58
00:08:00,230 --> 00:08:03,400
to Inspector Carp of Scotland Yard.

59
00:08:03,567 --> 00:08:07,947
Inspector, I'm terrified.
I tell you, it's gone beyond all reason.

60
00:08:08,114 --> 00:08:13,119
Lady Wolfington, there's only one way to tell
if a man has werewolf in his blood.

61
00:08:13,286 --> 00:08:16,582
He'll give himself away
by stammering ever so slightly...

62
00:08:16,748 --> 00:08:18,584
on all words beginning with "w".

63
00:08:18,751 --> 00:08:20,252
"W"?

64
00:08:20,253 --> 00:08:26,384
If you suspect your fiancé, put him to the test.
I'll get there as soon as I can.

65
00:08:29,305 --> 00:08:31,849
Oh, Freddy, you startled me.

66
00:08:32,015 --> 00:08:33,579
Startled?

67
00:08:33,601 --> 00:08:35,895
- By me?
- Yes, I'm sorry, I...

68
00:08:36,061 --> 00:08:39,753
All words beginning with "w".

69
00:08:40,024 --> 00:08:43,696
All words beginning with "w".

70
00:08:44,780 --> 00:08:47,325
Darling, what a lovely sweater.

71
00:08:47,492 --> 00:08:49,578
Is that cotton or wool?

72
00:08:49,744 --> 00:08:52,373
This? Oh, it's woo... wool.

73
00:08:52,539 --> 00:08:55,042
- What?
- Um...

74
00:08:56,251 --> 00:09:00,131
I say, uh... I don't know.
Must be some sort of a cotton.

75
00:09:03,260 --> 00:09:06,431
Oh, I think another storm's brewing.

76
00:09:16,316 --> 00:09:19,654
Seems so. Doesn't it?

77
00:09:27,411 --> 00:09:30,833
- Listen to that wind.
- Ooh-hoo!

78
00:09:30,999 --> 00:09:34,671
Oh! It's frightening, isn't it?

79
00:09:35,796 --> 00:09:37,674
- Why's he laughing?
- I don't know.

80
00:09:37,840 --> 00:09:40,885
- Is that how you rehearsed it?
- No, but that's Larry.

81
00:09:44,932 --> 00:09:48,019
- Darling, I'm going to have a sherry.
- Oh!

82
00:09:48,184 --> 00:09:52,607
- Would you or wouldn't you like some?
- Oh, I wou... I wou...

83
00:09:52,774 --> 00:09:56,445
Um... yes, I'll have some.

84
00:10:01,284 --> 00:10:04,121
- Here's your drink, darling.
- Thanks. Cheers.

85
00:10:04,287 --> 00:10:07,750
- To Wolfington Castle.
- To Woo... Woo...

86
00:10:07,917 --> 00:10:10,043
To Woo-woo-woo...

87
00:10:11,753 --> 00:10:14,215
To Woo-woo-woo-woo...

88
00:10:14,381 --> 00:10:15,945
Woo-woo-woo...

89
00:10:17,176 --> 00:10:18,742
To Woo-woo-woo...

90
00:10:18,887 --> 00:10:21,807
Woo-woo... To Woo-woo-woo...

91
00:10:21,974 --> 00:10:26,938
To Woo-woo-woo-woo... Wolfington Castle.

92
00:10:38,866 --> 00:10:41,789
- He's out. He's fired.
- No!

93
00:10:43,581 --> 00:10:47,086
- Who the hell are you?
- I'm Dr Paul Abbot.

94
00:10:47,252 --> 00:10:51,175
Oh, Doctor, thank God you're here.
Please come in.

95
00:10:51,341 --> 00:10:53,427
This is our sponsor, Mr Tarlow.

96
00:10:53,593 --> 00:10:57,056
Charlie, this is Larry's uncle,
the famous psychiatrist.

97
00:10:57,222 --> 00:11:00,602
- I asked him to come meet you.
- What's he laughing at?

98
00:11:00,767 --> 00:11:05,064
- This is a mystery, not a comedy.
- He's laughing because he's afraid.

99
00:11:05,231 --> 00:11:08,068
- Afraid?
- Tomorrow it might make him cry.

100
00:11:08,236 --> 00:11:11,614
That's what he did last week.
What's he afraid of?

101
00:11:11,615 --> 00:11:14,117
Thunder and lightning? A wind machine?

102
00:11:14,491 --> 00:11:18,706
We have that stuff every week.
Why now? We were number one!

103
00:11:18,871 --> 00:11:22,376
Because three weeks ago
he got engaged to be married.

104
00:11:22,542 --> 00:11:26,547
- The Curse of The Mummy.
- What's that got to do with it?

105
00:11:26,712 --> 00:11:29,759
The engagement has opened
a crack in his psyche,

106
00:11:29,927 --> 00:11:34,890
so hideous to Larry's mind
that he must lock it out.

107
00:11:35,055 --> 00:11:38,686
- But I do know that I can cure him.
- How?

108
00:11:40,187 --> 00:11:42,733
By scaring him...

109
00:11:42,899 --> 00:11:44,065
to death.

110
00:11:44,066 --> 00:11:48,948
- You want to scare him even more?
- How do you cure hiccups, Mr Tarlow?

111
00:11:49,114 --> 00:11:50,678
- Well, you...
- Listen...

112
00:11:50,783 --> 00:11:53,494
I've been working in Zurich
with a brilliant scientist...

113
00:11:53,661 --> 00:11:56,331
who has discovered
the cure for Larry's condition.

114
00:11:56,498 --> 00:12:03,005
Dr Strickland has proved the cure is to increase
the pressure of the fears, not lessen it.

115
00:12:03,173 --> 00:12:08,387
- Like going faster around a dangerous curve?
- Exactly.

116
00:12:08,552 --> 00:12:12,099
This weekend, starting tonight,
the entire Abbot family...

117
00:12:12,266 --> 00:12:15,978
is gathering for the wedding
at the estate of Larry's great-aunt.

118
00:12:16,145 --> 00:12:18,731
We have him in an ideal situation,

119
00:12:18,899 --> 00:12:22,486
a lonely estate, miles from anywhere.

120
00:12:24,320 --> 00:12:29,327
- Have you told Vickie?
- No, not Vickie, that'd be too risky.

121
00:12:29,493 --> 00:12:32,247
I'm afraid she couldn't be objective.

122
00:12:32,413 --> 00:12:34,667
Are you promising you can cure Larry?

123
00:12:34,833 --> 00:12:40,756
I, Paul Abbot, promise that
I can cure Larry within 36 hours.

124
00:12:40,924 --> 00:12:44,886
- Just by scaring him?
- By scaring him to death.

125
00:12:47,097 --> 00:12:53,187
I don't know. I can be feeling swell, then
something sets it off and I'm scared to death.

126
00:12:53,353 --> 00:12:56,733
So you acted nutty for a few shows, so what?

127
00:12:56,899 --> 00:13:02,157
You're the best actor in New York,
with the hottest show, and you still got me.

128
00:13:02,323 --> 00:13:06,535
So, listen, cookie, if something scares you
before Sunday, just say,

129
00:13:06,702 --> 00:13:10,331
"Whoops, there goes my imagination again.
How do you like that?"

130
00:13:10,497 --> 00:13:12,062
You think that'll work?

131
00:13:12,166 --> 00:13:16,422
Always in all ways rely upon me...

132
00:13:21,720 --> 00:13:25,349
Whoops, there goes my imagination again.
How do you like that?

133
00:13:25,516 --> 00:13:29,854
That's my guy. Did you hear what the bug
said to the windshield?

134
00:13:30,020 --> 00:13:32,566
- What?
- That's me all over.

135
00:13:33,691 --> 00:13:37,362
Sweet. Don't you get it? If a bug splattered...

136
00:13:37,529 --> 00:13:40,282
- Honey, is my tie straight?
- What?

137
00:13:40,447 --> 00:13:43,494
- Is my tie straight?
- Your tie's fine.

138
00:13:43,662 --> 00:13:47,082
- Yeah, but is it straight?
- Yeah, it's straight.

139
00:13:47,248 --> 00:13:48,811
Oh, good.

140
00:14:13,779 --> 00:14:18,326
Someone in this family is trying to kill me.

141
00:14:18,491 --> 00:14:22,205
What? You don't know what you're saying.

142
00:14:22,371 --> 00:14:28,170
Larry's the only one I trust.
Please give me the pen. I haven't much time.

143
00:14:28,336 --> 00:14:31,757
- They'll all be here any moment.
- I love you, Kate.

144
00:14:31,923 --> 00:14:35,636
I respect you as if you were my own mother.

145
00:14:35,804 --> 00:14:37,889
Oh...

146
00:14:38,765 --> 00:14:42,936
You're the dearest person I know.
I'd even die for you, Kate.

147
00:14:43,103 --> 00:14:47,942
But darling, never mind
that I'm a member of the family,

148
00:14:48,109 --> 00:14:51,446
before you sign, there's one 
thing you haven't considered.

149
00:14:51,612 --> 00:14:55,826
- What's that?
- What if Larry dies before you do?

150
00:14:55,993 --> 00:15:02,208
If Larry should die, you can all share 
the money equally, just as it was before.

151
00:15:02,375 --> 00:15:07,715
Francis, you're the only living person
that knows I've changed my will.

152
00:15:07,882 --> 00:15:13,096
If you ever tell anyone
may your soul rot in hell.

153
00:15:19,687 --> 00:15:23,942
What a cosy place for a wedding.
Who lived here before? Count Dracula?

154
00:15:24,107 --> 00:15:29,865
- Will you lay off that? I grew up here.
- No wonder you turned out so normal.

155
00:15:30,031 --> 00:15:34,537
- Hey, hey.
- Sorry. Must be delightful by daylight.

156
00:15:36,330 --> 00:15:41,128
- Run for it, sweetie. I'll get the bags.
- OK.

157
00:15:52,389 --> 00:15:56,896
Go on, honey, knock on the door.
I'll be right there.

158
00:16:25,929 --> 00:16:31,059
I'm... I'm engaged to Larry Abbot
and he... said he grew up here.

159
00:16:31,225 --> 00:16:34,771
Oh, you know... He...

160
00:16:34,939 --> 00:16:39,945
He was just... You know him, he says he...
Maybe I'm at the wrong house.

161
00:16:40,111 --> 00:16:42,239
I can come back, thank you.

162
00:16:42,405 --> 00:16:45,076
Sorry, honey. Oh, I see you've already met.

163
00:16:45,242 --> 00:16:47,724
I am Pfister, the family butler.

164
00:16:47,725 --> 00:16:50,645
And I'm the little boy you used
to tuck into bed...

165
00:16:50,706 --> 00:16:54,920
and bring milk and cookies to
just before you kissed me good night.

166
00:16:55,086 --> 00:16:57,298
- Your name, please?
- My name?

167
00:16:57,464 --> 00:17:01,593
- Is he kidding?
- Come in, Mr Kidding. I'll take the bags.

168
00:17:01,762 --> 00:17:04,264
Won't you follow me, please?

169
00:17:04,429 --> 00:17:08,643
- Poor Pfister, his memory's going.
- I wish we were.

170
00:17:11,856 --> 00:17:14,275
This way, please.

171
00:17:16,736 --> 00:17:22,534
- Holy smokes. You grew up in this place?
- I learned to ride a bike in this room.

172
00:17:22,701 --> 00:17:27,873
- He gives me the willies.
- Be nice to him. He seems strange but he isn't.

173
00:17:28,039 --> 00:17:31,837
- What'll I talk about?
- Talk about a minute, that'll be enough.

174
00:17:32,003 --> 00:17:36,008
Be very careful of that 
magnificent vase on the landing.

175
00:17:36,174 --> 00:17:39,929
There are only three like it in the entire world.

176
00:17:40,095 --> 00:17:42,600
Oh, what kind is it?

177
00:17:42,765 --> 00:17:45,602
Twenty-five past seven.

178
00:17:46,771 --> 00:17:49,816
- A little hard of hearing...
- What?

179
00:17:49,982 --> 00:17:54,529
- A little hard of hearing. It comes and goes.
- What?

180
00:17:54,695 --> 00:17:57,116
My fiancée, she's a little hard of hearing.

181
00:17:57,282 --> 00:17:58,909
- Come and goes, eh?
- Yes.

182
00:17:59,075 --> 00:18:02,705
I'll remember that. This way, miss!

183
00:18:02,872 --> 00:18:04,958
This is gonna be some weekend.

184
00:18:21,727 --> 00:18:23,896
Toby! Toby, shush!

185
00:18:27,358 --> 00:18:30,111
Who is it? Who's there?

186
00:18:30,278 --> 00:18:32,989
What? Pfister!

187
00:18:33,156 --> 00:18:38,787
Why are these windows still open?
Do I have to do everything? Drunken sot!

188
00:18:38,953 --> 00:18:41,415
Hold your horses! Where's Pfister?

189
00:18:41,581 --> 00:18:45,378
Where is he? Oh, I'm coming, I'm coming.

190
00:18:51,177 --> 00:18:56,891
Who are you? What do you want?
This is just for the family. I don't know you.

191
00:18:57,058 --> 00:19:01,730
Why are you looking at me?
What do you want? Are you selling something?

192
00:19:11,240 --> 00:19:15,078
Oh, please, forgive me.

193
00:19:15,245 --> 00:19:20,585
Is there any way I can help you, sir?

194
00:19:20,751 --> 00:19:26,175
I'm Montego. My wife is Susan Abbot.
She should be here any moment.

195
00:19:26,342 --> 00:19:31,139
I came from Philadelphia by train.
I believe the family's expecting me.

196
00:19:31,306 --> 00:19:33,309
Won't you come in?

197
00:19:46,197 --> 00:19:50,327
- Have you got any luggage, sir?
- Just this one case.

198
00:19:50,493 --> 00:19:53,206
Oh, it's a large one, isn't it?

199
00:19:53,372 --> 00:19:56,292
Would you like me to...?

200
00:19:57,418 --> 00:20:01,632
I prefer to handle it myself, thank you.

201
00:20:21,070 --> 00:20:24,824
Now if anything frightens you,
anything at all, you just holler.

202
00:20:24,992 --> 00:20:28,453
- I'll be right down the hall, OK?
- OK.

203
00:20:42,386 --> 00:20:45,014
Just practising.

204
00:20:49,018 --> 00:20:51,062
I love you, cookie.

205
00:20:51,228 --> 00:20:54,817
- See you in 20 minutes.
- OK.

206
00:20:54,983 --> 00:20:56,548
Da-da-da

207
00:20:57,361 --> 00:21:00,615
- Master Larry!
- Pfister, you do remember me.

208
00:21:00,781 --> 00:21:06,080
- Of course. When did you get here?
- About 15 minutes ago.

209
00:21:06,246 --> 00:21:08,541
If I'd known, I'd have greeted you.

210
00:21:08,707 --> 00:21:12,921
Yes, that would have been nice.
Well, we can't have everything.

211
00:21:13,086 --> 00:21:16,008
- Come along, you're in your old room.
- Oh, good.

212
00:21:17,093 --> 00:21:22,056
- So what do you think, honey?
- Wow, what a snazzy little nook.

213
00:21:22,221 --> 00:21:25,935
Rachel, Rachel, you're a 
sight for sore eyes, baby.

214
00:21:26,101 --> 00:21:29,147
Oh, Rachel...

215
00:21:31,358 --> 00:21:36,155
- She usually plants a big, wet one on me.
- I do not!

216
00:21:36,322 --> 00:21:38,324
She must be shy.

217
00:21:38,492 --> 00:21:44,498
Rachel, I'd like you to meet a very old friend
of mine from school, Sylvia Beecham.

218
00:21:44,665 --> 00:21:46,376
Pleased to meet you, Rachel.

219
00:21:46,542 --> 00:21:50,046
Rachel, you look wonderful.
Not a day over seventy...

220
00:21:50,213 --> 00:21:54,135
- three? Four? Seventy-five... Six. Oh, Rachel.
- You need a haircut.

221
00:21:54,300 --> 00:21:57,764
Oh, same old Rachel. Love you, baby, love you.

222
00:21:57,930 --> 00:22:00,600
- Where's Larry?
- He's upstairs.

223
00:22:00,766 --> 00:22:05,480
Come on, I'll take you on the grand tour, huh?

224
00:22:12,614 --> 00:22:16,243
Rachel, did you get the note
about the connecting rooms?

225
00:22:16,409 --> 00:22:20,163
- What? What's that?
- I knew that would get to her.

226
00:22:25,878 --> 00:22:30,007
If you don't mind me saying,
